article.headline: Gophers force overmatched foes into 24 turnovers
article.linkText: No. 13 Minnesota impresses its coach with defense
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota continues to pile up the points,
but coach Pam Borton is more impressed with how the Gophers (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today; No. 12 Associated Press) are playing defense.

	   While Lindsay Whalen scored 21 points, Minnesota forced
Missouri-Kansas City into 24 turnovers and 18-for-47 shooting in an
easy 88-53 victory Friday in Minneapolis.

	   ''I was very pleased with our intensity defensively for 40
minutes,'' said Borton, in her first year as head coach of the Gophers. ''That's something we've been emphasizing.
We accomplished about 95 percent of what we wanted to do on
defense.''

	   Many of the turnovers were converted into fastbreak
opportunities, and nearly all resulted in easy baskets for the
unbeaten Gophers (8-0).

	   ''We had a little bit of fun with some fastbreaks,'' Whalen
said. ''We wish we could have finished a few more of those.''

	   Corrin Von Wald went 7-for-8 from the field for 20 points and Kim Prince
added 10 for Minnesota, which entered the game with the nation's
top scoring offense at 89.3 points a game.

	   Katie Houlehan led the Kangaroos (2-4) with 13 points, and Casey
Ellis and Randi Meissner each added 12.

	   Minnesota scored 13 of the game's first 15 points. During a
four-minute span midway through the first half, Whalen scored nine
consecutive points as the Gophers extended their lead to 24-11.

	   Von Wald hit two free throws just before halftime to give
Minnesota a 40-19 lead at the break. The Gophers opened the second
half with a 20-5 run.

	   ''We're disappointed, but not down by any means,'' said Kansas
City coach Dana Eikenberg. ''A lot of things we worked on we
executed well. But we've got to get back to work and master the
fundamentals.''

	   The Gophers' only home game in December drew 6,109 to Williams
Arena, the largest non-conference home crowd in Minnesota women's
basketball history.
